Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "[Bug]: Some packets are pushed slowly to nuget.server" (#8900) at NuGet/NuGetGallery
Events.RelatedBody:
### NuGet Product Used

MSBuild.exe, NuGet.exe

### Product Version

nuget.exe 5.11.0.10, msbuild  16.11.1.47101, nuget.server 3.4.1.0

### Worked before?

_No response_

### Impact

It's more difficult to complete my work

### Repro Steps & Context

1. step one: create some nupkg packages using msbuild xml.  The following code is used to build the package

`<MSBuild Projects="$(BuildSolutionDir)/Mares.Scheduler.Api.Client/Mares.Scheduler.Api.Client.csproj" Targets="Restore" />
<MSBuild Projects="$(BuildSolutionDir)/Mares.Scheduler.Api.Client/Mares.Scheduler.Api.Client.csproj"
				 Targets="Build;Pack"	Properties="Configuration=$(Configuration);PackageOutputPath=$(NuGetPackageDir);Authors=$(Authors);Version=$(Version)" />`


2. step two: push packages with a powershell script to nuget server (hosted in iis 10).  some package need 250ms to be pushed, other need more than 30sec.  The following is the code I use to push the package

`$PackagePath = "$(Get-Location)\Packages"
Get-ChildItem $PackagePath -Filter *.nupkg|
Foreach-Object {
    Invoke-Expression "$($NugetPath) push $($_.FullName) -Source $($NugetApi) -ApiKey $($NugetApiKey) -Verbosity detailed" 
    Remove-Item $_.FullName
}`

The strange behaviour occur when publishing new packets and when replacing existing packets.  It looks like nuget server rebuild some cache


Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "Add support for requesting nomination data for projects" (#6575) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
GetPackageSpec should block and request nomination info from the project system when there is no data present. The current behavior is to return null which ultimately causes a failed restore when project details are missing.

This requires a way to query the project system for that information instead of just waiting until it is pushed to the nomination API.

### Expected flow
Test explorer **->** NuGet **->** Project system

A request for installed packages requires the list of PackageReference entries. When the call is received NuGet should block and request the information from the project system in order to get the information.

### Actual flow
Test explorer **->** NuGet **<-** Project system

Since both arrows are incoming for NuGet, it can't block. Instead it just gives up immediately when it doesn't have the data. Other times NuGet returns out of date information.

### Examples
* Test explorer often fails to determine if a project has xunit installed because NuGet throws an exception until the project system pushes the needed info.
* Auto restore fails with an error related to missing project details. NuGet is unable to determine if all nomination info has been sent.
* Back to back package operations fail. For example: install, then uninstall. Uninstall does not see the latest project info because the project system is still processing it and will fail saying that the package isn't installed.

Relevant code:
https://github.com/NuGet/NuGet.Client/blob/7fc2573b76fceb8a007a25012027c5b829c0801a/src/NuGet.Clients/NuGet.PackageManagement.VisualStudio/Projects/NetCorePackageReferenceProject.cs#L110-L118

Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "NuGet doesn't emit a warning when it relies on PackageTargetFallback" (#6925) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
## Details about Problem
Project's using PackageTargetFallback don't emit a warning so folks are often unknowingly using a package that may not be compatible with what they are targeting

NuGet product used (NuGet.exe | VS UI | Package Manager Console | dotnet.exe):
dotnet.exe & VS

NuGet version (x.x.x.xxx):

dotnet.exe --version (if appropriate):
2.1.300-rc1-008673

VS version (if appropriate):
15.7 preview 4

OS version (i.e. win10 v1607 (14393.321)):
win10 1709 (16299.431)
 
Worked before? If so, with which NuGet version:
Don't know

## Detailed repro steps so we can see the same problem

1. dotnet new console, targeting netcoreapp2.0 or netcoreapp2.1.
2. Add reference to <PackageReference Include="Newtonsoft.Json" Version="6.0.8" />
3. dotnet restore.
4. Observe warning `warning NU1701: Package 'Newtonsoft.Json 6.0.8' was restored using '.NETFramework,Version=v4.6.1' instead of the project target framework '.NETCoreApp,Version=v2.1'. This package may not be fully compatible with your project.`  This is good.
5. Change project to use PackageTargetFallback: 
```xml
    <DisableImplicitAssetTargetFallback>true</DisableImplicitAssetTargetFallback>
    <PackageTargetFallback>net461</PackageTargetFallback>
```
6. dotnet restore
7. Observe no warning.  This is bad

### Sample Project
```xml
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">

  <PropertyGroup>
    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>
    <TargetFramework>netcoreapp2.1</TargetFramework>
    <DisableImplicitAssetTargetFallback>true</DisableImplicitAssetTargetFallback>
    <PackageTargetFallback>net461</PackageTargetFallback>
  </PropertyGroup>
  
  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="Newtonsoft.Json" Version="6.0.8" />
  </ItemGroup>

</Project>
```


I understand that the warning addition was part of the AssetTargetFallback feature, but for the same reason that we needed it there we need it on PackageTargetFallback as well (since PTF isn't deprecated and still used).

Example:
https://github.com/aspnet/Entropy has dozens of projects. Restoring produces this warning:

> C:\dotnet\sdk\1.0.0-rc4-004757\NuGet.targets(97,5): warning : Detected package downgrade: NETStandard.Library from 1.6.2-beta-24913-01 to 1.6.1 \r [C:\dev\Universe\Entropy\Entropy.sln]

Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "Consider deprecating `Source` parameter" (#5435) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
### Problem

Specifying a source when installing a package in `PackageRef` or `project.json` project won't make any effect on subsequent restores, because v3 restore operation will always look for best match across all **listed** sources.  Hence install operation will fail eventually. Moreover it might confuse user as providing one of listed sources won't give it a preference when resolving packages.

Behavior is similar for PMC `Install-Package` and for extension APIs.

### Solution
Consider deprecating `Source` parameter by marking the API as obsolete for v3. At minimum give meaningful error or warning message. Update documentation. Package Manager UI should use `All Sources` by default.
